\c 25
\cl Isaias 25
\cd A canticle of thanksgiving for God's judgments and benefits.
\p
\v 1 O Lord, thou art my God, I will exalt thee, and give glory to thy name; for thou hast done wonderful things, thy designs of old, faithful, Amen.
\p
\v 2 For thou hast reduced the city to a heap, the strong city to ruin, the house of strangers to be no city, and to be no more built up for ever.
\p
\v 3 Therefore shall a strong people praise thee; the city of mighty nations shall fear thee.
\p
\v 4 Because thou hast been a strength to the poor, a strength to the needy in his distress: a refuge from the whirlwind, a shadow from the heat. For the blast of the mighty is like a whirlwind beating against a wall.
\p
\v 5 Thou shalt bring down the tumult of strangers, as heat in thirst: and as with heat under a burning cloud, thou shalt make the branch of the mighty to wither away.
\p
\v 6 And the Lord of hosts shall make unto all people in this mountain, a feast of fat things, a feast of wine, of fat things full of marrow, of wine purified from the lees.
\p
\v 7 And he shall destroy in this mountain the face of the bond with which all people were tied, and the web that he began over all nations.
\p
\v 8 He shall cast death down headlong for ever: *and the Lord God shall wipe away tears from every face; and the reproach of his people he shall take away from off the whole earth: for the Lord hath spoken it.
\p
\v 9 And they shall say in that day: Lo, this is our God, we have waited for him, and he will save us: this is the Lord, we have patiently waited for him, we shall rejoice and be joyful in his salvation.
\p
\v 10 For the hand of the Lord shall rest in this mountain: and Moab shall be trodden down under him, as straw is broken in pieces with the wain.
\p
\v 11 And he shall stretch forth his hands under him, as he that swimmeth stretcheth forth his hands to swim: and he shall bring down his glory with the dashing of his hands.
\p
\v 12 And the bulwarks of thy high walls shall fall, and be brought low, and shall be pulled down to the ground, even to the dust.
\x + \xo 25:8\xt Apocalypse 7:17.; Apocalypse 21:4.\x*
\f + \fr 25:1\ft Amen. He approves of God's judgments (Haydock) against Jerusalem. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 25:2\ft City; Jerusalem, or rather Babylon, (chap. 21.) (Calmet) or every city (Haydock) in the world. (Menochius) --- Strangers: the temples of idols.\f*
\f + \fr 25:3\ft People; the Chaldeans, or their conquerors.\f*
\f + \fr 25:4\ft Poor; Juda, whom Nabuchodonosor's fury could not exterminate.\f*
\f + \fr 25:5\ft Away. Cyrus (Calmet) shall reduce Babylon the great. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 25:6\ft Mountain of Sion, a figure of the Church, and of heaven. The Jews shall feast: yea, some of all nations shall partake of the blessed Eucharist, and obtain heaven. The expressions are too grand for a corruptible feast. (Calmet) --- Wine. Literally, "of vintage," (Haydock) on which occasion great rejoicings were made. (Hesiod, Hercul. 297.) --- Protestants, "of wines on the lees." (Haydock) --- In the East, the wines were very thick, Psalm 75:9. (Calmet) --- On the rejection of the Jews, the Gentiles were converted. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 25:7\ft Tied. He will open their eyes to the truth of the gospel. They shall be no longer as criminals, expecting death, or mourning.\f*
\f + \fr 25:8\ft Ever. Hebrew, "he shall swallow up death in victory," 1 Corinthians 15:54. Christ, by dying, conquered death, and rescued us from its power, if we do not voluntarily subject ourselves to it again. This was faintly represented by the liberation of the captives.\f*
\f + \fr 25:10\ft Mountain: the Church. (Calmet) --- Moab. That is, the reprobate, whose eternal punishment, from which they can no way escape, is described under these figures. (Challoner) --- The Machabees probably executed this vengeance on Moab, 1 Machabees 5:6.\f*
\f + \fr 25:11\ft Hands. All his exertions and fury will prove useless. (Haydock) --- Moab shall lie prostrate.\f*
<>
\c 26
\cl Isaias 26
\cd A canticle of thanks for the deliverance of God's people.
\p
\v 1 In that day shall this canticle be sung the land of Juda. Sion, the city of our strength, a Saviour, a wall, and a bulwark, shall be set therein.
\p
\v 2 Open ye the gates, and let the just nation, that keepeth the truth, enter in.
\p
\v 3 The old error is passed away: thou wilt keep peace: peace, because we have hoped in thee.
\p
\v 4 You have hoped in the Lord for evermore, in the Lord God, mighty for ever.
\p
\v 5 For he shall bring down them that dwell on high; the high city he shall lay low. He shall bring it down even to the ground; he shall pull it down even to the dust.
\p
\v 6 The foot shall tread it down; the feet of the poor, the steps of the needy.
\p
\v 7 The way of the just is right; the path of the just is right to walk in.
\p
\v 8 And in the way of thy judgments, O Lord, we have patiently waited for thee: thy name, and thy remembrance are the desire of the soul.
\p
\v 9 My soul hath desired thee in the night: yea, and with my spirit within me, in the morning early, I will watch to thee. When thou shalt do thy judgments on the earth, the inhabitants of the world shall learn justice.
\p
\v 10 Let us have pity on the wicked; but he will not learn justice: in the land of the saints he hath done wicked things, and he shall not see the glory of the Lord.
\p
\v 11 Lord, let thy hand be exalted, and let them not see: let the envious people see, and be confounded: and let fire devour thy enemies.
\p
\v 12 Lord, thou wilt give us peace: for thou hast wrought all our works for us.
\p
\v 13 O Lord, our God, other lords besides thee have had dominion over us, only in thee let us remember thy name.
\p
\v 14 Let not the dead live, let not the giants rise again: therefore hast thou visited and destroyed them, and hast destroyed all their memory.
\p
\v 15 Thou hast been favourable to the nation, O Lord, thou hast been favourable to the nation: art thou glorified? thou hast removed all the ends of the earth far off.
\p
\v 16 Lord, they have sought after thee in distress; in the tribulation of murmuring thy instruction was with them.
\p
\v 17 As a woman with child, when she draweth near the time of her delivery, is in pain, and crieth out in her pangs, so are we become in thy presence, O Lord.
\p
\v 18 We have conceived, and been as it were in labour, and have brought forth wind: we have not wrought salvation on the earth, therefore the inhabitants of the earth have not fallen.
\p
\v 19 Thy dead men shall live, my slain shall rise again: awake, and give praise, ye that dwell in the dust: for thy dew is the dew of the light: and the land of the giants thou shalt pull down into ruin.
\p
\v 20 Go, my people, enter into thy chambers, shut thy doors upon thee, hide thyself a little for a moment, until the indignation pass away.
\p
\v 21 *For behold the Lord will come out of his place, to visit the iniquity of the inhabitant of the earth against him: and the earth shall disclose her blood, and shall cover her slain no more.
\x + \xo 26:21\xt Micheas 1:3.\x*
\f + \fr 26:1\ft Day. Under the law of grace, Christians sing this and such like canticles. (Worthington) --- Sion. This word is not in Hebrew, etc., though it be understood. (Calmet) --- Other nations have their respective cities. All Christians admit this one. (Worthington) --- The captives continue to return thanks. Yet the Holy Ghost speaks chiefly of the Church, and of the general resurrection. (Calmet) --- Bulwark. Faith and good works. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 26:2\ft Truth. The Jews who returned from Babylon, were more virtuous than their ancestors, as the prophets intimate; though they have Christians principally in view.\f*
\f + \fr 26:3\ft Away: condemning the virtuous, as if they were fools. (Menochius) --- Symmachus, "our work, or fiction, is taken away." Hebrew may have other meanings. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 26:4\ft You, people of Juda.\f*
\f + \fr 26:5\ft High: Nabuchodonosor and his empire.\f*
\f + \fr 26:6\ft Needy. The Jews shall behold the ruin of the city by Cyrus, (Calmet) who was of a contemptible nation. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 26:7\ft In. God will remove every obstacle, at their return.\f*
\f + \fr 26:9\ft Night of distress.\f*
\f + \fr 26:10\ft Justice. Clemency would therefore be ill placed. If the Israelites had not been led away captives, would they ever have been reformed?\f*
\f + \fr 26:11\ft Not see. Let them perish, or live to witness the glory of the Jews.\f*
\f + \fr 26:12\ft Works, both in punishing and rewarding. (Calmet) --- God crowns his own gifts. (Estius)\f*
\f + \fr 26:13\ft Lords of Babylon, (Calmet) and our own passions. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 26:14\ft Giants; the proud emperors of Babylon, whom thou wilt destroy. Septuagint, "physicians;" as Rephaim has also this meaning.\f*
\f + \fr 26:15\ft Nation of the Jews. (Calmet) --- Septuagint, "add evils to them, O Lord; add evils to the nobles of the land." (Haydock) --- Hebrew may have the same sense. --- Ends: princes, or the Chaldeans, sending them also into captivity; or thou hast propagated thy Church over the world.\f*
\f + \fr 26:16\ft They. Septuagint, "We," etc. (Calmet) --- Affliction is a wholesome medicine. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 26:18\ft Wind. Our expectation of aid from others has been disappointed. (Calmet) --- Septuagint, "the spirit of thy salvation, which thou hast wrought on the earth. We shall not fall, but the inhabitants of the earth shall fall." (Haydock) --- Their copies must have been different from ours. --- Fallen. The Chanaanites are left for our trial and punishment. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 26:19\ft Dead: a civil death, shall regain their liberty; and those who have left this world in a state of virtue, shall be happy. --- Ruin. Cyrus liberated the Jews, having conquered Babylon.\f*
\f + \fr 26:20\ft Away, and Cambyses be destroyed, Ezechiel 38:11. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 26:21\ft Shall cover her stain no more. This is said with relation to the martyrs, and their happy resurrection. (Challoner) --- The blood of the saints shall demand vengeance. (Calmet)\f*
